### 8. Signaling RSVP-TE Tunnels on an SR-MPLS Forwarding Plane Using Adjacency Segment Identifiers
* **Slide Presentation:** [08 - Signaling RSVP-TE Tunnels on an SR-MPLS Forwarding Plane Using Adjacency Segment Identifiers](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mpls-08-signaling-rsvp-te-tunnels-on-an-sr-mpls-forwarding-plane-using-adjacency-segment-identifiers-01)
* **Presenter:** Pavan Beeram

#### Discussion:
* Pavan Beeram introduced a new draft proposing the use of SR adjacency sets to establish a shared forwarding plane for RSVP-TE tunnels. This unifies the forwarding plane and eliminates duplicate label systems when running both SR and RSVP-TE.
* Alexander Vainshtein asked about the interaction between protected adjacency SIDs and facility-based Fast Reroute (FRR).
* Pavan Beeram clarified that the draft leverages existing RFC 8577 and RFC 4090 procedures, using a dedicated protection SID at the PLR to distinguish between protected and unprotected states.
* Zafar Ali spoke against the draft, stating that introducing signaling state into segment routing goes against the core "stateless" architecture of SR.
* Pavan Beeram responded that this solution is aimed at scenarios where operators want to run a shared forwarding plane but still require distributed bandwidth engineering, which currently depends on RSVP-TE.
* Himanshu Shah raised a question regarding EXP/Traffic Class bit propagation on the label stack. Pavan Beeram agreed to add clarifying text on EXP propagation to the draft.

